(17, 'Application of ict in your daily lives as a broadcasting students', 20, 500, 1, 10, 30, 'ICT\'s day to day living for broadcasting students, is an improvement in leaming as well as a fun aspect of it. With internet enabled resources in the form of videos, tutorials, and articles, stadents easily access information applicable to learning the principles of broadcasting Media proshaction of shadents on their career wise earnings is applied in different software that produces different media such as video editing and graphic design software geared towards their making professional materials. They are alio trained in the use of social media related avenues to market themselves and interact with audiences. Enhanced communication and networking of shalents are able to exchange information with industry experts and fellow students in online forums, learning frown them, and creating links that might lead to future employment. There are also technologies for getting recent and relevant news and developments about the industry instantly, which students will be able to use to keep up with the rapid changes in the media environment. Broadcasting students can even use time management apps to plan their year and adjust meeting expectations like those of school work. ICT is not only an assistant for broadcasting students, it is the key elements that enhances their learning and preparing them for good careers in this increasingly dynamic media landscape. ICT has changed the daily lives of students by upgrading and thus improving their learning experience as well as making it interesting. With such resources put online videos, tutorials, and descriptive articles seeking relevant information to learn the principles of broadcasting becomes an easier task for students. Apart from this, they also capture skills on how to utilize social media in self marketing while\r\nYou sent\r\nengaging their audiences. Enhanced communication and networking and online forums allow students to interact with industry experts and other fellow students for information sharing and relationship development that could lead to future employment. In addition, these technologies provide instant accessibility to the latest happenings and trends within the industry, which keeps on evolving rapidly; hence, with that, the students keep up with the pace. To schedule and prioritize their tasks accordingly for better management of their school life, broadcasting students could make use of time-management apps. So, ICT is not merely an aid to broadcasting students, it is an essential ingredient that aids in their learning process and equips for profitable careers in an increasingly dynamic media landscape.', NULL, NULL, 24),
(18, 'What is the historical significance of the Alberto Mansion, and what evidence presented in the documentary suggests its connection to Dr. Jose Rizal\'s family? Additionally, what alleged family secrets of Dr. Jose Rizal were mentioned in the documentary? Discuss the importance of uncovering such historical revelations and their impact on our understanding of Rizals legacy.', 20, 1000, 1, 15, 31, 'The documentary reveals that truly there is no really perfect family, even our national hero Jose Rizals is no exemption. He has a secret that he wanted to hide to the world. However, the discumentary entitled Ang Lihim ng Pamilya ni Rizal, is a revelation that the universe holds no secrets that just like Rizal, his secrets are slowly unfolding and revealed to the people. Moreover, the film captures the reality of the family disputes, controversies, and secrecy that any person does not want to reveal to anyone. In details, the documentary able to provide context and analysis on various aspects of Rizals life, Firstly, his matriarchal family relationship, and the issue on legitimacy of Teodora Alonso, which is the mother of Rizal, as well as the legitimacy of Soledad as the youngest daughter of Teodora. This theory is something that needs for further research and needs for evidence to accept as truth. But this give me a perception that this theory can be possible once proven by a historian, Secondly, the family feud and conflicts that led to the arrest of Rizals mother. This clearly describes the kind of justice system that we had during the Spanish rule in the Philippines, Rizals mother and his family experience first hand the injustices of the colonial rule. Because the film reveals that she was accused of poisoning the wife of his brother namely Teodora Formosa. The arrest and trial are questionable since the other party uses personal connection for personal gain and in particularly in order to make Rizals mother accountable of the murder attempt that they believed, wherein, this led to two years of imprisonment of Doa Teodora. This made me realized that even until now our current justice system did not improve since then. Because there are many innocent individuals are in serving in jail due to the inadequate legal representation is the process of trials and prosecutorial misconduct. In conclusion, this film provides as with intriguing insights into secrets surrounding Rizals family life. A reminder that life is full of mystery and there are many more hidden stories that needs to unfold to reveal the truth', NULL, NULL, 25),
(19, 'Should Filipino raised outside the phillipines considered within Filipino Psychology  \r\nwhy? or why not?', 20, 1000, 1, 15, 32, 'vvcxcx|Yes, They Should Be Considered Within Filipino Psychology\r\nFilipinos raised outside the Philippines should still be considered within Filipino Psychology (Sikolohiyang Pilipino) because cultural identity is not solely based on physical location. Many Filipinos growing up abroad are raised in households that strongly uphold Filipino traditions, values, and practices. They learn concepts such as pakikisama (harmony in relationships), utang na loob (debt of gratitude), and hiya (sense of propriety), which are fundamental to Filipino Psychology. These values shape their thinking, behavior, and decision-making, even in a foreign environment. Additionally, Filipino migrant communities around the world actively maintain their cultural identity through language, customs, and celebrations, reinforcing the psychological connection to their heritage.\r\n\r\nAnother key argument is the Filipino concept of kapwa, or shared identity. Filipino Psychology emphasizes that being Filipino is not just about nationality but also about recognizing a deep sense of interconnectedness with others. Filipinos raised abroad who still practice kapwa, value strong family ties, and engage with Filipino culture continue to be part of the psychological framework. Furthermore, many overseas Filipinos face experiences of migration, adaptation, and cultural negotiation, which reflect the resilience and collectivist mindset deeply ingrained in Filipino Psychology. Even if they are influenced by other cultures, their Filipino upbringing continues to shape their worldview and interactions.|No, They Should Not Be Considered Within Filipino Psychology\r\nOn the other hand, some argue that Filipinos raised outside the Philippines should not be fully considered within Filipino Psychology because their experiences, upbringing, and environment differ significantly from those of Filipinos living in the homeland. Filipino Psychology is deeply rooted in the social realities of the Philippines, such as economic struggles, community life, and traditional family structures. Those who grow up in other countries may not face the same societal challenges, leading to a psychological framework shaped more by their host country than by Filipino norms.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, growing up in a different culture can lead to a dilution or transformation of Filipino values. While some Filipinos abroad may still practice certain traditions, their overall worldview and behavior are often influenced by Western or other foreign cultural perspectives. For example, individualism is more dominant in many Western societies, whereas Filipino Psychology is deeply collectivist. This difference affects how individuals perceive relationships, decision-making, and personal responsibilities. Furthermore, language plays a critical role in shaping Filipino Psychology, as many of its core concepts are rooted in Filipino linguistic structures. If a Filipino raised abroad does not fluently speak Filipino languages, their understanding of psychological traits such as loob (inner self) or pakikiramdam (shared inner perception) may be limited or influenced by Western interpretations.', NULL, NULL, 26),
(20, '\r\n Explain the process of bone remodeling, and bone repair.\r\n', 20, 500, 1, 10, 33, 'The bone remodeling begins with bone resorption by osteoclast, a specialized cells that break down the mineralized bone matrix. This is followed by the reversal phase, where mononuclear cells prepare the bone surface for the subsequent formation phase. Osteoblasts, derived from mesenchymal stem cells, then synthesize and deposit new bone matrix, which later becomes mineralized, restoring bone strength. The process is regulated by systemic hormones like parathyroid hormone (PTH) and calcitonin, as well as local factors including cytokines, growth factors, and signaling molecules such as RANKL (Receptor Activator of Nuclear Factor Kappa-B Ligand), RANK (its receptor on osteoclasts), and osteoprotegerin (a decoy receptor that inhibits RANKL).\r\nBone repair, on the other hand, occurs in response to fractures or injuries and follows distinct yet overlapping phases: inflammation, repair, and remodeling. During the inflammation phase, blood vessels at the injury site break, forming a hematoma. This leads to the recruitment of inflammatory cells and the release of cytokines and growth factors like fibroblast growth factor (FGF) and vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF), which initiate healing. In the repair phase, a soft callus forms as cartilage and woven bone are laid down by chondrocytes and osteoblasts. The soft callus is gradually replaced by a hard callus made of mineralized bone. Finally, in the remodeling phase, the hard callus undergoes reshaping to restore the bone\'s original structure and strength through the coordinated activity of osteoclasts and osteoblasts. Pathways such as the Wnt/-catenin pathway play a pivotal role in osteoblast differentiation, while the TGF- (Transforming Growth Factor Beta) pathway regulates various stages of repair.\r\n\r\n', NULL, NULL, 27),
(21, 'With automation and AI advancing, many jobs are evolving or disappearing. However, new opportunities are also being created.\r\n\r\nProblem:\r\n\r\nIf you were advising students about future career paths, what three fields or skills would you recommend they focus on to stay relevant? Justify your recommendations and provide insights on how technology will shape these fields.\r\n', 20, 500, 1, 10, 34, 'As automation and artificial intelligence reshape the job market, students must prepare for careers that combine technological proficiency with uniquely human skills to remain relevant. Three key fields stand out as promising pathways for the future. First, STEM disciplines, particularly AI and data science, are essential, as they drive innovation across industries. While AI automates routine tasks, human expertise remains critical in developing algorithms, interpreting data, and addressing ethical concerns. Students should focus on programming, machine learning, and interdisciplinary applications, such as AI in healthcare or finance. Second, human-centered professions like healthcare, education, and psychology will continue to thrive because they rely on empathy, adaptability, and complex decision-makingqualities that machines cannot replicate. Technology will augment these fields through telemedicine and AI-assisted learning, but human judgment and emotional intelligence will remain irreplaceable. Finally, green and sustainable technology is rapidly growing due to global climate challenges. Careers in renewable energy, environmental engineering, and circular economies will be in high demand as societies transition toward sustainability, supported by AI-driven solutions like smart grids and pollution monitoring. To succeed, students should cultivate a hybrid skill setmerging technical knowledge with creativity, ethics, and problem-solvingwhile embracing lifelong learning to adapt to an ever-evolving workforce. By focusing on these areas, they can secure meaningful careers that leverage both human ingenuity and technological advancements.\r\n\r\n', NULL, NULL, 28),
(22, 'How do entrepreneurs drive economic growth and innovation through Joseph Schumpeter\'s concept of \"creative destruction,\" and how has their role evolved from the earliest periods to the 21st century? Additionally, what are some common challenges they face, such as [Challenge 1] and [Challenge 2], and how can these challenges impact business success?', 100, 1500, 1, 100, 35, 'ANSWER \r\n1.	Why is an entrepreneur considered important in economic growth? Explain using Joseph Schumpeter\'s idea of \"creative destruction.\"\r\nEntrepreneurs play a pivotal role in driving economic growth by introducing innovations, reshaping industries, and fostering competition. Joseph Schumpeter, an Austrian economist, introduced the concept of \"creative destruction,\" which explains how entrepreneurs propel economic progress by replacing outdated technologies and business models with more efficient and innovative alternatives. According to Schumpeter (1950), an entrepreneur is someone who transforms a new idea or invention into a successful innovation, which disrupts existing industries, making older processes obsolete and paving the way for new opportunities. Creative destruction occurs when innovative products, services, and technologies emerge, rendering previous methods or goods irrelevant. This process, while disruptive to established businesses, generates long-term economic benefits by increasing productivity, creating new industries, and expanding markets. For example, the invention of the automobile replaced horse-drawn carriages, and more recently, streaming platforms like Netflix disrupted traditional cable television. These innovations not only improved convenience and efficiency but also stimulated economic growth by generating demand for new products and services. In this way, entrepreneurs serve as catalysts for change, ensuring that economies remain dynamic, adaptable, and competitive. \r\n\r\n2.	How has the role of entrepreneurs changed from the earliest period to the 21st century? Give examples of how entrepreneurship has evolved over time.\r\nThe role of entrepreneurs has significantly evolved from the earliest period to the 21st century, reflecting the changing nature of economic systems, societal needs, and technological advancements.\r\n\r\n\r\nEarliest Period: Entrepreneurship initially focused on establishing trade routes and facilitating commerce. Entrepreneurs during this period acted as merchants who transported goods between distant regions, assuming high risks due to unpredictable trade conditions and uncertain profits\r\n Middle Ages: In the Middle Ages, entrepreneurship expanded to managing large production projects. Entrepreneurs, often in the form of clerics and managers, oversaw architectural endeavors such as the construction of castles and cathedrals. They were responsible for organizing labor, managing resources, and ensuring project completion. \r\n17th Century: The 17th century marked a shift where entrepreneurs began to take on greater financial risks. Governments awarded contracts for services and stipulated products, and entrepreneurs bore the risk of profit or loss. During this period, the association betweeri risk and entrepreneurship became more prominent. \r\n18th Century: Entrepreneurship was formally recognized, with Richard Cantillion (1725) defining entrepreneurs as individuals who purchase goods at known prices and sell them at uncertain future prices. This period distinguished entrepreneurs from capital providers, emphasizing the risk-taking and innovative functions of entrepreneurs. \r\n19th Century: The 19th century broadened the entrepreneurial concept, highlighting the entrepreneur\'s role in combining factors of production, managing resources, and assuming risks. J.B. Say and Francis Walker emphasized that entrepreneurial profits were distinct from the returns on capital, underlining the value of innovative and managerial skills. \r\n20th Century: Joseph Schumpeter revolutionized the understanding of entrepreneurship by linking it to innovation and \"creative destruction.\" Entrepreneurs in this period were seen as agents of change who reformed production patterns, introduced technological advancements, and drove economic transformation. \r\n21st Century: Today, entrepreneurship is characterized by its association with innovation in a highly competitive and globalized environment. Modern entrepreneurs focus on introducing new technologies, business models, and services that address emerging consumer needs. Digital platforms, artificial intelligence, and e-commerce are prime examples of contemporary entrepreneurial endeavors that have transformed industries. For instance, Elon Musk\'s ventures in electric vehicles (Tesla) and space exploration (SpaceX) demonstrate how 21st-century entrepreneurs leverage technology to create revolutionary products that redefine industries. \r\n\r\n3.	What are some common challenges that entrepreneurs face? Choose two challenges and explain how they can affect the success of a business.\r\nEntrepreneurs encounter numerous challenges that can significantly impact the success and sustainability of their ventures. Two of the most common challenges are: \r\n1.	Lack of Favorable Environment\r\nEntrepreneurship thrives in an environment where essential elements such as capital, skilled labor, customer interest, and government support are readily available. However, in societies where these factors are lacking, entrepreneurs struggle to establish and grow their businesses. For instance, inadequate access to funding can hinder the innouative ideas while the absence of a skilled workforce may lead to discourage entrepreneurial activities. In such environments, entrepreneurs may find it difficult to scale their operations, limiting their ability to contribute to economic growth and innovation. \r\n2.	Resistance Against Innovations and Changes Societies that resist change and lack a culture of research and innovation can pose a\r\nsignificant barrier to entrepreneurship. When a society is rooted in traditional ideologies and is reluctant to embrace new ideas, entrepreneurs may struggle to introduce innovative solutions. For example, industries accustomed to conventional practices may resist adopting advanced technologies, leading to slower growth and limited competitiveness. Additionally, societal skepticism toward unconventional business models can make it difficult for entrepreneurs to gain market acceptance and secure funding. This resistance to change not only discourages innovation but also hampers the potential for transformative growth, ultimately affecting the long-term success of entrepreneurial\r\n\r\n', NULL, NULL, 29),
