(26, 'How Generative AI Affects academic Performances of Students?', 100, 500, 1, 100, 36, 'The rise of generative AI, such as ChatGPT and similar tools, is having a significant impact on the academic performance of students. These technologies are transforming the way students access, understand, and engage with educational content. When used appropriately, generative AI can be a powerful tool for enhancing learning. One of its major benefits is the improved access to knowledge it provides. Students can ask questions and receive immediate answers on complex topics, allowing them to study at their own pace and beyond traditional classroom hours. This helps reinforce learning and deepen comprehension, especially when in-person support is limited.\r\n\r\nMoreover, generative AI supports the development of writing and research skills. Students often use these tools to brainstorm ideas, structure essays, and correct grammar mistakes. This can lead to more polished work and improved confidence in their academic writing. In addition, AI tools can serve as personalized tutors, offering explanations that cater to individual learning styles and needs. For example, if a student is struggling with a particular math concept, an AI tool can walk them through the steps until they understand, making study time more efficient and productive.\r\n\r\nLanguage support is another area where generative AI proves to be valuable. Students who are not fluent in the language of instruction benefit from tools that can translate or simplify complex text, making it easier to grasp and engage with their academic materials. This inclusive approach helps bridge language barriers and improves educational outcomes for a broader range of learners.\r\n\r\nHowever, while the advantages of generative AI are clear, there are also significant concerns about its impact on academic integrity and independent learning. One major drawback is the risk of over-reliance. If students begin to depend too heavily on AI for completing assignments, it can hinder the development of essential skills like critical thinking, problem-solving, and creativity. Instead of learning how to analyze or construct arguments on their own, students may rely on AI to do the work for them, which can negatively affect their intellectual growth in the long term.\r\n\r\nAnother pressing concern is the rise in academic dishonesty. Some students may use AI to write entire essays or solve problems without understanding the underlying content, leading to plagiarism and unethical behavior. This not only undermines the educational process but also creates unfair advantages and calls into question the validity of academic achievements. Educational institutions are now facing the challenge of how to integrate AI tools ethically into learning environments while maintaining academic standards.\r\n\r\nIn conclusion, generative AI has the potential to significantly enhance student learning and academic performance when used responsibly. It offers personalized support, improves access to knowledge, and assists with writing and language comprehension. However, students and educators must remain mindful of its limitations and the ethical issues it presents. By encouraging responsible use and promoting AI as a complement to, rather than a replacement for, learning, its benefits can be fully realized without compromising academic integrity.', NULL, NULL, 33),
