(156, 41, 28, 'If I were to advise a student about their future career, I would strongly recommend focusing on science, computer, and engineering fields. These disciplines are not only in high demand in our country but also essential in our rapidly evolving world. Technology continues to grow at an unprecedented pace, making these fields more crucial than ever. Innovations in these areas enhance efficiency, accuracy, and productivity, transforming industries and improving daily life.\r\n\r\nA great example is Geodetic Engineering, where technological advancements have revolutionized traditional methods. In the past, land surveying required extensive manual labor and time-consuming processes. Today, with tools like RTK (Real-Time Kinematic) drones, large areas can be mapped with just a single click, significantly speeding up data collection while improving precision. This is just one of many ways technology is reshaping careers in science and engineering, making them more dynamic and impactful.\r\n\r\nBy pursuing these fields, students can position themselves at the forefront of innovation, ensuring long-term career relevance and the opportunity to contribute to meaningful advancements in society. The future belongs to those who embrace technology, and these disciplines offer the perfect foundation for success.', NULL, NULL),
(157, 42, 28, 'The rapid advancement of artificial intelligence and automation is fundamentally transforming the job market, with smart machines increasingly handling tasks that once required human labor. From manufacturing to data analysis, AI-driven technologies are becoming more autonomous, displacing traditional roles while simultaneously creating new opportunities. This paradigm shift makes career planning both more challenging and more critical than ever before.\r\n\r\nIn this evolving landscape, the key to future-proofing your career lies in strategic skill development. Rather than resisting technological progress, forward-thinking individuals should focus on cultivating expertise in areas where human capabilities complementrather than compete withmachine intelligence. The most resilient career paths will be those that leverage uniquely human strengths like creativity, emotional intelligence, and complex problem-solving, while incorporating technical proficiency in emerging technologies.\r\n\r\nFields such as AI development, robotics engineering, and data science offer exciting prospects, as these disciplines actually drive technological innovation rather than being displaced by it. Similarly, healthcare, education, and creative industries continue to value human judgment and interpersonal skills that machines cannot replicate. Sustainable technology and green energy sectors present particularly promising opportunities as global priorities shift toward environmental solutions.\r\n\r\nThe most successful professionals of tomorrow will be those who adopt a growth mindset, viewing technological change not as a threat but as an opportunity to upskill and adapt. By focusing on interdisciplinary knowledgecombining technical expertise with soft skillsand remaining agile in the face of change, today\'s students can position themselves to thrive in the workplaces of the future. The challenge isn\'t to compete with machines, but to develop the irreplaceable human qualities that will define value in the AI era.', NULL, NULL),
(158, 43, 28, 'If I were advising students about future career paths, I would strongly emphasize developing advanced digital literacy and IT competencies. In our 21st-century world, technology has become the backbone of nearly every industryfrom healthcare and finance to education and entertainment. Whether a student aspires to be an artist, entrepreneur, or scientist, technological fluency will be their most valuable asset. Basic IT skills are now the minimum requirement, while advanced programming, data analysis, or cybersecurity knowledge can provide a significant competitive edge.\r\n\r\nFor students with diverse skill setssuch as communication, graphic design, teaching abilities, or project managementI would highly recommend exploring freelancing and digital entrepreneurship. The gig economy is booming, fueled by emerging technologies like 5G networks, blockchain, and AI-powered platforms. While freelancing demands discipline and adaptability, it offers unparalleled flexibility and global opportunities. A graphic designer, for instance, can now collaborate with international clients using cloud-based tools, while a tutor can leverage AI-assisted platforms to personalize learning experiences.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, I would encourage students to consider engineering in its broadest sense. While Civil Engineering remains essential for infrastructure development, fields like AI engineering, renewable energy systems, and smart city design are becoming increasingly vital. Modern engineers dont just build bridgesthey develop sustainable solutions, integrate IoT (Internet of Things) into urban planning, and automate industrial processes. As technology evolves, engineers who adapt to innovations like machine learning, robotics, and augmented reality (AR) will lead the next wave of progress.\r\n\r\nUltimately, the key to future career success lies in continuous learning and versatility. Students should focus on hybrid skillscombining technical expertise with creativity, problem-solving, and adaptabilityto thrive in an ever-changing job market. By embracing technology rather than fearing it, they can turn challenges into opportunities and secure fulfilling, future-proof careers.', NULL, NULL),
(160, 45, 28, 'As automation and artificial intelligence continue to transform the professional landscape, students and young professionals must adapt by cultivating a versatile skill set that combines human creativity with technological proficiency. Three key areas of focus stand out as particularly valuable in this evolving environment: advanced editing capabilities, innovative content creation, and foundational technical competencies.\r\n\r\nMastering AI-assisted editing skills positions individuals at the forefront of digital content production. Modern editing tools powered by machine learning can dramatically enhance productivity, but they still require human oversight for quality control, creative direction, and nuanced decision-making. Professionals who can skillfully leverage these tools while maintaining editorial judgment will find abundant opportunities in fields ranging from video production to academic publishing and corporate communications.\r\n\r\nContent creation and ideation represents another critical skillset where human ingenuity remains irreplaceable. While AI can generate content, it lacks authentic creativity and the ability to connect with audiences on an emotional level. Developing strong conceptual thinking, storytelling abilities, and visual communication skills enables professionals to craft compelling narratives and innovative solutions that stand out in crowded digital spaces. This skillset proves valuable across marketing, education, entertainment, and corporate strategy.\r\n\r\nFoundational technical skills form the third pillar of future-ready professional development. Basic programming literacy, data analysis capabilities, and digital tool proficiency serve as force multipliers for any career path. These competencies not only improve one\'s ability to work alongside advanced technologies but also create pathways to specialize in emerging fields like AI implementation, automation management, or tech-enabled creative industries.\r\n\r\nThe most successful professionals will be those who approach these skills not in isolation, but as interconnected capabilities. An editor with technical skills can optimize AI tools more effectively, a content creator with data literacy can better measure audience engagement, and a technically-skilled professional with creative abilities can bridge the gap between development and implementation. This interdisciplinary approach, combined with a commitment to continuous learning, will define career resilience in the coming decades.\r\n\r\nUltimately, the key to thriving in an automated future lies not in competing with machines, but in developing the uniquely human capacities that technology cannot replicate, while simultaneously harnessing AI as a powerful collaborative tool. This balanced approach offers both professional stability and the opportunity to shape how emerging technologies transform our world.', NULL, NULL),
(163, 48, 29, 'Entrepreneurs serve as the lifeblood of economic growth by continuously introducing innovations that reshape markets and consumer behavior. Joseph Schumpeter\'s groundbreaking concept of \"creative destruction\" perfectly captures this dynamic process - where entrepreneurial innovations systematically disrupt outdated technologies and business models, creating space for more efficient and advanced alternatives. This constant cycle of renewal and improvement is what keeps economies vibrant and competitive in the global marketplace.\r\n\r\nThe evolution of entrepreneurship reflects humanity\'s technological and social progress. In ancient times, entrepreneurial activity centered around basic trade and artisan craftsmanship within local communities. The Industrial Revolution marked a dramatic shift, with visionary entrepreneurs like Henry Ford pioneering assembly line production that fundamentally transformed manufacturing capabilities. The digital revolution brought forth a new generation of innovators like Bill Gates and Steve Jobs, whose technological breakthroughs reshaped how we work, communicate and access information. Today\'s entrepreneurial landscape is characterized by digital platforms, AI-driven startups, and global e-commerce ventures that transcend traditional geographical boundaries.\r\n\r\nDespite their critical role, entrepreneurs face persistent challenges that test their resilience. Access to startup capital remains a significant barrier, as traditional financial institutions often hesitate to fund unproven ventures. Equally daunting is the challenge of cash flow management - many promising businesses falter not because of poor products or services, but due to timing mismatches between income and expenses. These financial hurdles highlight why financial literacy and strategic planning are indispensable skills for any aspiring entrepreneur.\r\n\r\nThe enduring lesson is clear: while the forms of entrepreneurship may change with technological progress, its fundamental importance to economic vitality remains constant. Societies that nurture entrepreneurial talent and remove unnecessary barriers to innovation position themselves for sustained prosperity in an increasingly competitive global economy.', NULL, NULL),
(171, 49, 29, 'Entrepreneurs serve as vital drivers of economic progress by introducing transformative ideas that reshape industries. Joseph Schumpeter\'s principle of \"creative destruction\" demonstrates how they propel economies forward by replacing outdated systems with superior alternatives. Companies like Amazon revolutionized retail through e-commerce, while Uber and Grab redefined urban mobility with ride-sharing platforms. These innovations not only generate employment but also enhance productivity, maintaining economic competitiveness in an ever-evolving global market.\r\n\r\nThe evolution of entrepreneurship mirrors humanity\'s technological and commercial development. Ancient merchants along the Silk Road established early trade networks, while Industrial Revolution pioneers like Henry Ford transformed manufacturing through assembly line production. In the modern era, visionaries including Steve Jobs and Bill Gates fundamentally altered communication through personal computing. Today\'s digital landscape continues this tradition, with platforms like Facebook illustrating how contemporary entrepreneurship increasingly focuses on digital solutions and service-based models.\r\n\r\nYet entrepreneurial success requires overcoming significant obstacles. Access to capital presents a persistent challenge, as many promising ventures struggle to secure adequate funding for growth. A local artisanal food producer, for instance, may have exceptional products but limited resources for expansion. Additionally, new entrants must differentiate themselves in competitive markets dominated by established players. Successful entrepreneurs navigate these challenges by developing unique value propositions, delivering exceptional service, or identifying underserved market niches.\r\n\r\nFrom ancient trading routes to today\'s digital marketplace, entrepreneurs have consistently advanced societies by identifying needs and creating innovative solutions. While their tools and methods have evolved, their fundamental ability to recognize and capitalize on opportunities remains unchanged. This enduring entrepreneurial spirit continues to be essential for building resilient, forward-looking economies capable of adapting to future challenges and opportunities.', NULL, NULL),
(184, 50, 29, 'Entrepreneurs play a crucial role in economic growth, as explained by Joseph Schumpeters concept of creative destruction. According to Schumpeter, entrepreneurs drive progress by introducing innovations that replace outdated industries, leading to increased efficiency, competition, and job creation. For example, the rise of e-commerce platforms like Amazon has significantly disrupted traditional retail stores, while ride-sharing services like Uber have transformed the taxi industry, fostering economic development through innovation and technological advancement. Over time, the role of entrepreneurs has evolved significantly, adapting to different economic periods. In ancient and medieval times, entrepreneurs were primarily traders and merchants, such as those along the Silk Road, who facilitated international commerce. The Industrial Revolution saw entrepreneurs like Henry Ford, who revolutionized mass production through the assembly line, shaping modern manufacturing. In the 20th century, the concept of franchising emerged, with companies like McDonalds expanding businesses through standardized systems. In the 21st century, entrepreneurship has further evolved with the rise of tech startups, digital platforms, and the gig economy, with companies like Tesla and Airbnb redefining transportation, accommodation, and sustainability in business. However, despite their significant contributions, entrepreneurs face several challenges that can affect business success. One major challenge is financial constraints, as securing capital is often difficult for new businesses. Without adequate funding, entrepreneurs struggle to invest in production, marketing, or hiring employees, limiting their ability to scale. Another challenge is market competition, where new businesses must compete against well-established brands with greater resources, customer loyalty, and brand recognition. This competition can make it difficult for startups to gain market share, requiring them to develop unique value propositions and effective strategies to survive.', NULL, NULL),
(187, 51, 29, 'Entrepreneurs are vital to economic growth, driving progress by introducing innovative ideas, products, and services that enhance efficiency, productivity, and consumer choice. Joseph Schumpeters concept of creative destruction highlights how entrepreneurs replace outdated products, services, and business models with more efficient and advanced alternatives. For instance, the rise of e-commerce platforms like Amazon and Shopee has significantly diminished the dominance of physical retail stores by offering convenience, wider selections, and competitive pricing. While this shift presents challenges for traditional businesses, it also fuels economic development by fostering innovation, competition, and new market opportunities.\r\n\r\nThe role of entrepreneurs has evolved drastically from ancient times to the 21st century. In the early period, entrepreneurs were primarily traders and craftsmen, selling goods in local markets and engaging in long-distance commerce, such as the Silk Road merchants who facilitated global trade. The Industrial Revolution marked a turning point, with pioneers like Henry Ford revolutionizing mass production through the assembly line, making goods more affordable and accessible. In the 20th century, corporate entrepreneurship flourished, with multinational corporations like McDonalds and Coca-Cola expanding worldwide. In the 21st century, rapid advancements in technology and digital platforms have transformed entrepreneurship, making it more accessible and scalable than ever. Entrepreneurs can now launch businesses online, develop mobile apps, and sell handmade products through e-commerce websites with minimal startup costs, enabling even individuals to reach a global audience.\r\n\r\nDespite these opportunities, entrepreneurs face numerous challenges, with financial constraints and market competition being among the most significant. Many struggle to secure funding to start or scale their businesses. Without sufficient capital, they may be unable to develop products, invest in marketing, or hire skilled employees, limiting their potential for growth. Additionally, market competition is fierce, as new businesses must compete with established brands that have greater resources, customer loyalty, and pricing power. Startups that fail to effectively market their products and differentiate themselves risk being overshadowed by larger competitors. However, adaptability, innovation, and strategic planning can help entrepreneurs overcome these obstacles and thrive, proving that entrepreneurship remains a powerful force in driving economic progress.', NULL, NULL),
(194, 52, 29, 'Entrepreneurs play a crucial role in economic growth by introducing new ideas and innovations that reshape industries. Joseph Schumpeter\'s \"creative destruction\" explains how new businesses replace outdated ones, driving progress despite challenges. For example, Grab and Uber changed transportation by offering more convenient alternatives to taxis, while Netflix and Spotify replaced DVDs and CDs. Though these shifts can be difficult for older businesses, they lead to better products, more jobs, and economic progress.\r\n\r\nEntrepreneurship has evolved over time, adapting to technological and societal changes. In ancient times, trade took place in local markets. The Industrial Revolution brought factories and mass production, changing how goods were made. The 20th century saw the rise of franchises like McDonald\'s, allowing businesses to expand faster. Today, digital platforms and the internet help businesses grow globally, making it easier for startups to compete with big companies.\r\n\r\nDespite their impact, entrepreneurs face challenges, such as financial struggles and market competition. Many startups find it hard to afford rent, salaries, and supplies, causing some to close within their first year, especially in countries like the Philippines. Solutions include finding investors, government support, or crowdfunding. Competition is another challenge, with big brands like Jollibee and McDonald\'s dominating the market. To stand out, small businesses must offer unique products, better services, or new ideas.\r\n\r\nFrom local markets to the digital age, entrepreneurs continue to shape economies by adapting to changes and overcoming challenges. Their ability to innovate and take risks keeps businesses growing and industries evolving.', NULL, NULL),
(195, 53, 29, 'Entrepreneurs have long played a central role in shaping economies, driving innovation, and challenging the status quo. At the heart of their impact lies economist Joseph Schumpeters concept of creative destructiona powerful force by which entrepreneurs introduce innovations that disrupt existing markets, ultimately leading to economic progress. As the global landscape evolves, so too has the role of the entrepreneur, shifting from local tradespeople in early civilizations to tech-savvy visionaries in the modern digital economy. Along the way, entrepreneurs have faced a variety of challenges that continue to influence their chances of success or failure.\r\n\r\nSchumpeters theory of creative destruction emphasizes that entrepreneurial innovation is not a smooth or incremental process. Instead, it involves disrupting outdated systems, replacing old industries with new ones, and continuously reshaping the economic order. Entrepreneurs are the catalysts of this transformation. They develop new technologies, reimagine traditional industries, and implement fresh business models that often render previous methods obsolete. For instance, the invention of the automobile eliminated the need for horse-drawn carriages, and digital streaming services like Netflix replaced physical video rentals. This continuous cycle of renewal, though at times turbulent, is essential for economic dynamism and progress.\r\n\r\nThe role of entrepreneurs has evolved significantly throughout history. In pre-industrial societies, entrepreneurs were typically artisans, merchants, or small-scale innovators who contributed to local economies through limited, incremental changes. The Industrial Revolution, however, marked a turning point. Entrepreneurs like Andrew Carnegie and John D. Rockefeller used large-scale capital investments to create vast business empires, revolutionizing steel, oil, and transportation industries. Moving into the 20th century, the expansion of consumer markets, corporate structures, and access to venture capital enabled entrepreneurs to scale innovations like never before.\r\n\r\nIn the 21st century, entrepreneurship has become more democratized and digitally driven. The proliferation of the internet, mobile technology, and globalized commerce allows individuals to launch startups with fewer resources and from virtually anywhere. Entrepreneurs like Elon Musk and Sara Blakely exemplify how creativity, risk-taking, and adaptability can disrupt traditional sectorsautomotive and fashion, respectively. Moreover, todays entrepreneurs are increasingly concerned with social impact, sustainability, and ethical innovation, reflecting broader societal values.\r\n\r\nDespite their vital role, entrepreneurs face numerous challenges that can threaten the viability of their ventures. One significant obstacle is access to capital. Many entrepreneurs struggle to secure sufficient funding to develop their products, expand operations, or endure lean periods. Without adequate financial support, startups may stagnate or collapse before reaching their full potential. While options like angel investors, venture capital, and crowdfunding offer potential solutions, navigating these avenues can be competitive and uncertain.\r\n\r\nAnother common barrier is regulatory complexity. Entrepreneurs must often comply with a labyrinth of legal and bureaucratic requirements, including business licenses, tax codes, labor laws, and industry-specific regulations. For small or early-stage businesses, managing compliance can consume valuable time and resources, hindering innovation and operational efficiency. Regulatory uncertainty can also deter investment and slow the momentum of otherwise promising enterprises.\r\n\r\nTo overcome these challenges, entrepreneurs must be resourceful and resilient. Building strong networks, seeking expert mentorship, and staying informed about policy developments are crucial strategies. Additionally, governments and institutions play a pivotal role by fostering environments that encourage entrepreneurshipthrough supportive regulation, access to funding, and investment in education and infrastructure.\r\n\r\nIn conclusion, entrepreneurs are engines of economic growth and innovation, embodying Schumpeters vision of creative destruction. Their evolving role across history highlights their adaptability and importance in reshaping economies. Yet, as they drive change, entrepreneurs must also contend with significant barriers, including financial limitations and regulatory pressures. By addressing these challenges through strategic planning and supportive ecosystems, we can ensure that entrepreneurship continues to thrive and contribute to a more dynamic and prosperous future.', NULL, NULL),
